  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The 50% Fibonacci midpoint of an order block's body range (body high to low). Price should not close beyond it for the block to remain valid. Used as an alternative entry to improve risk-to-reward, especially when the opening price lies outside the OTE zone.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a valid order block (or propulsion block, breaker block) with displacement and change in state of delivery.",
    "Measure the body range from body high to body low (open to close), ignoring wicks.",
    "Mark the 50% level (0.5 Fibonacci) of that body range as the mean threshold.",
    "For a bullish order block, price must not close below the mean threshold on retest; for a bearish order block, not above. A close beyond invalidates the order block.",
    "If the candle has large wicks and a small body, use the 50% Fibonacci from close to wick extreme instead of body midpoint.",
    "For optimized entry, use the 0.85 Fibonacci level of the body range (body low + (body high - body low) × 0.85).",
    "Use the mean threshold as an alternative entry when the order block's opening price lies outside the OTE zone or yields unfavorable risk-to-reward; enter on a confirmed reaction with a stop beyond the OB extreme.",
    "When a propulsion block forms off the original order block, its mean threshold should be respected under the same rules.",
    "Check that the order block's opening price is not already in the OTE zone; if it is, prefer the opening price over the mean threshold."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The mean threshold provides an alternative entry within an order block, reducing stop distance and improving risk-to-reward, especially when the opening price lies outside the OTE zone. It serves as a tighter invalidation point: a close beyond it signals the order block has failed. Respect at the mean threshold, including on subsequent propulsion blocks, confirms the trade's validity. Can be combined with other PD arrays for confluence. Do not use alone; require narrative direction and confirmation.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing mean threshold with the order block's opening price.",
    "Measuring the mean threshold using wicks instead of only the candle body (open to close).",
    "Treating a wick beyond the mean threshold as invalidation; only a candle close beyond invalidates the order block.",
    "Failing to recognize that a close beyond the mean threshold invalidates the order block, even if other levels remain untouched.",
    "Placing the stop directly at the mean threshold without a buffer, or moving the stop from the swing low/high to the mean threshold.",
    "Applying the mean threshold without a valid order block (no displacement, no change in state of delivery).",
    "Entering at the mean threshold without waiting for a confirming reaction (e.g., reversal candle).",
    "Assuming every order block will respect the mean threshold without verifying it has not already been diminished or broken.",
    "Using the mean threshold on non-order-block zones (e.g., fair value gaps) where the concept does not apply.",
    "Defaulting to the order block's opening price when the mean threshold would provide a better entry (e.g., opening price outside OTE zone).",
    "Using the mean threshold when the order block's opening price is already in the OTE zone, instead of using the opening price.",
    "Confusing mean threshold with Fair Value Gap's consequent encroachment (FVG 50% level).",
    "Ignoring timeframe alignment: confirm on higher timeframe before applying on lower timeframe."
  ],
